\par }\pard\plain \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {
\par Bridge is a game played by four people divided into two teams.  The players sit around a table with the teammates (also called partners) sitting across the table facing each other.  The four player positio
ns are assigned the compass positions of North, East, South, and West.  Note that the designations are usually relative to each observer; i.e., from your vantage point as a player you would usually consider yourself South, looking across at your partner i
n the North position.
\par 
\par Each hand of Bridge consists of two stages, }{\i Bidding}{ and }{\i Card Play}{.  The bidding stage (also called the }{\i auction}{) occurs first, followed by the card play.  One or more }{\i hands}{ are played in a single }{\i game}{
, and two or three games are played in a }{\i match}{, called a }{\i rubber}{.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs20 {
