\par After the end of the bidding, the card play begins with the player to the left of the }{\i declarer}{.  The declarer is the player on the team with the winning bid who first bid the suit the team final
ly ended up in.  This is actually not as complicated as it might first sound.
\par 
\par As an example, if a player bids 1H, and his partner 2D, and the final contract is 3H, the first player would be the declarer, since he first bid Hearts.  Alternatively, if a pla
yer bids 1H, partner 2D, and the final contract is 5D, the second player would be the declarer, since he first bid Diamonds, the final contract suit.
\par 
\par The declarer is also often called the }{\i Driver}{, as he will play the cards for the partnership.  Conversely, the Driver\rquote s partner becomes the }{\i Dummy}{, as he no longer participates in the card play stage (as explained later).
\par 
\par The lead player (once again, on the declarer\rquote s left), starts by taking a card from his hand and placing it face up on the table.  The play t
hen proceeds clockwise around the table as each player in turn places one of his cards face up on the table.  
\par 
\par If the current player holds one or more cards in the suit that was led, he must play a card from that suit \endash  this is called }{\i following suit}{.  If he does not have any cards in the suit led (he is }{\i void}{
 in the suit), he may play a card of a different suit, including a trump, if one was declared in the contract.  Note that this means a player has the option of playing a trump }{\i only}{ when he is void in the suit that was led.
\par 
\par After the first player leads a card, the dummy in the declaring team places all of his cards on the table face up, arranged by suit.  This makes his cards visible to his partner as well as the opponents.  From this point on, the decla
rer plays the cards for dummy\rquote s hand as well as his own. Note, however, that he }{\i cannot}{ play a card from his own hand when it is dummy\rquote s turn, or vice versa.
\par 
\par After all four players have played a card, the trick or round is awarded to the player who played the highest card in the suit led.  If however one or more trump cards have been played, the highest trump card wins the trick.  
\par 
\par Note that a card that does not match the suit led, and which is also not a trump card, is never eligible to win a trick.  For this reason, playing a card that is not of the suit led and not a trump is called a }{\i discard}{.
\par 
\par At the end of each round, the player who played the winning card collects the cards from the round and places it in front of him.  That player then leads the first card of the next round.
\par 
\par At the end of 13 rounds, the number of tricks won by each team is added up.  If the declaring side makes the number of tricks promised, they have made or fulfilled the contract and are awarded trick points.  If they exceed the promised number of tricks, t
